            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>The koinon Kinakon, at its own expense, (honours) Markos Iounios Phelix, councillor of the Lilybaetanans, who has been zealous for his fatherland. For a worthy patron, by decree of the councillors and council(?).</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>The resolution of the final abbreviation is very uncertain. Manni-Piraino suggests also the alternative of 'dono dedit benmerentissimo', although the rendering of a Latin formula would be perhaps even more unusual. The engraved symbol of a crown at the start of line 8 perhaps suggests that Felix was also honoured with a crown (this stele was presumably part of the base of a statue?). The nominative form of the koinon's name is uncertain (kinakes or kinakoi), as is the nature of the association itself, which has been suggested to be a punic name, derived from the Canaanite ethnic, and so conceivably referencing a group of merchants from the eastern Mediterranean or North Africa; or else an association of dyers of purple. See also the entry in the Copenhagen Associations Project <ref target="http://ancientassociations.ku.dk/assoc/1291">http://ancientassociations.ku.dk/assoc/1291.</ref><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--Brugnone does not make explicit whether she reports the text from autopsy, and in fact checking the photograph and comparing texts, Bisi's text is more accurate than Brugnone's; but Brugnone provides a full bibliography. BE reports M-P's publ, which confirms the corrections of Segre for the reading. The inscr. is in honour of Iounios Phelix, bouleutes Lilubaeiton. At the end are the letters d.d.b. (gr.), which M-P asserts are not dogma dekourionon boules, but dono dedit benmerentissimo. For 'koinon kinakon', M-P follows Segre in thinking it's a punic name. Conjectures that it may be a variant on the Canaanite ethnic, and thus that this marks a resident group of 'Phoenicians' engaged in trade at Mazara. The AE notice has a full text, after Segre, with the observation that the koinon kinakon perhaps 'une association religieuse'. (koinon, cf. Lintott (1993), 178 with refs). I now have p'copy of the Manni Piraino article (Inst of Arch stores) on file. Also three colour prints + negatives of the stone, and brief notes, from visit 1.7.02.--></p>
            </div>
